title: For Sale:  1911A1 pistol, Remington, Dulith finish
postcontent: Remington 1911A1 pistol. Early, Dulith finish. Serial # 971,896 with NO prefix rather than an underlined No. Although some publications list this serial number as March 1943 production, it may have been finished after production was started again in May-June ’43 (after shutdown in Feb.) with the new on site Ordnance inspector. He designated that new production pistols would have the NO prefix to distinguish newly produced pistols. Since old receivers were used up in new production a mix of NO and No can be found in serial number range 955,000 to 1,016,000. This pistol has the Du-lite finish with some blued parts. Regulations required the same finish on the receiver and slide but parts could be other finishes. Slide is type 2 with markings 1 3/8” long and ending in N.Y.U.S.A. Type 2 slides started about #935,000. Blued High Standard barrel. P stamped on the left side of the lug, HS on the right. Bore is mirror with a little micro erosion from firing. Feed ramp is bright with traces of finish, not polished. Recoil spring plug is blued. Remington narrow hammer. Finely checkered early Remington mainspring cover. Blued checkered slide stop (Colt). Blued safety checkered on top and bottom with no undercut (Colt). Colt supplied these parts to Remington until Remington could make them. Front sight has sloped serrated ramp on rear. Rounded cut on front of rear sight with squared aperture. Early Keyes grips without re-enforcing rings around screws. No hits, bangs or smashed checkering. Bluing on pistol is about 95%. There is some wear on the top of the barrel and on other moving parts. Du-lite was not as sturdy as Parkerizing. Heat treated area on end of the slide is very visible but there is none above the slide stop. The slide stop area was not included in heat treating until sometime after April 1943. Blued checkered magazine release. Magazine is General Shaver manufacturer with G on the toe, spot welded plate and welded seam on the back. An excellent early Remington with only slight handling wear.

title: For Sale:  Finnish capture 1941 Russian SVT-40 Tokarev
postcontent: This rifle is a fine example of the more desirable Finnish captured Russian SVT-40 Tokarev. It is not import marked, no electro-pencil on any parts. The receiver is marked with the “SA” Finish Army ownership mark as well as the bottom of th magazine. The top of the receiver is marked with the Tula Arsenal “star”, “1941”.The rifle is in very good or better condition overall - nicer than most Finnish marked SVT-40s. The metal retains a respectable amount of original blue combined with honest, even wear and silvering of blued surfaces. Many more pictures of firearm condition and arsenal marks available to emailThe mechanics are excellent and it has the Finn-added "2" setting on the gas adjustment nut. The bore has strong rifling, has near-mirror shine from chamber to some scattered light pitting toward the muzzle. Most SVT-40s are found with heavily pitted bores. This one is really nice for an SVT-40. The pictures of the bore are shown in order from chamber end to muzzle end.The rifle was made during WWII by the Russians and was probably used to fight the Nazis. Later it was captured by the Finnish Army during the Continuation War and was probably used against the Russian.Call/text 52O-432-6O7I for more information. CCW holder, with Gunbroker and eBay accounts for feedback. Can show in Bisbee or Tucson. Considering Best Reasonable Offers for sale. Thank you for your interest.
